# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: session-fixation-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] An **HTTP cookie** (also called **web cookie**, **Internet cookie**, **browser cookie**, or simply **cookie**) is a small block of data created by a web server while a user is browsing a website and placed on the user's computer or other device by the user's web browser.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are placed on the device used to access a website, and more than one cookie may be placed on a user's device during a session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Cookies serve useful and sometimes essential functions on the web.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] They enable web servers to store stateful information (such as items added in the shopping cart in an online store) on the user's device or to track the user's browsing activity (including clicking particular buttons, logging in, or recording which pages were visited in the past).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] They can also be used to save information that the user previously entered into form fields, such as names, addresses, passwords, and payment card numbers for subsequent use.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The term *cookie* was coined by web-browser programmer Lou Montulli.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] It was derived from the term *magic cookie*, which is a packet of data a program receives and sends back unchanged, used by Unix programmers.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Magic cookies were already used in computing when computer programmer Lou Montulli had the idea of using them in web communications in June 1994.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] At the time, he was an employee of Netscape Communications, which was developing an e-commerce application for MCI.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Vint Cerf and John Klensin represented MCI in technical discussions with Netscape Communications.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] MCI did not want its servers to have to retain partial transaction states, which led them to ask Netscape to find a way to store that state in each user's computer instead.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Cookies provided a solution to the problem of reliably implementing a virtual shopping cart.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Together with John Giannandrea, Montulli wrote the initial Netscape cookie specification the same year.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Version 0.9beta of Mosaic Netscape, released on 13 October 1994, supported cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The first use of cookies (out of the labs) was checking whether visitors to the Netscape website had already visited the site.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Montulli applied for a patent for the cookie technology in 1995, which was granted in 1998.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Support for cookies was integrated with Internet Explorer in version 2, released in October 1995.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The introduction of cookies was not widely known to the public at the time.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In particular, cookies were accepted by default, and users were not notified of their presence.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The public learned about cookies after the *Financial Times* published an article about them on 12 February 1996.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In the same year, cookies received a lot of media attention, especially because of potential privacy implications.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Federal Trade Commission hearings in 1996 and 1997.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The development of the formal cookie specifications was already ongoing.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In particular, the first discussions about a formal specification started in April 1995 on the www-talk mailing list.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A special working group within the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) was formed.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Two alternative proposals for introducing state in HTTP transactions had been proposed by Brian Behlendorf and David Kristol respectively.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] But the group, headed by Kristol himself and Lou Montulli, soon decided to use the Netscape specification as a starting point.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In February 1996, the working group identified third-party cookies as a considerable privacy threat.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The specification produced by the group was eventually published as RFC 2109 in February 1997.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] It specifies that third-party cookies were either not allowed at all, or at least not enabled by default.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] At this time, advertising companies were already using third-party cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The recommendation about third-party cookies of RFC 2109 was not followed by Netscape and Internet Explorer.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] RFC 2109 was superseded by RFC 2965 in October 2000.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] RFC 2965 added a `Set-Cookie2` header field, which informally came to be called "RFC 2965-style cookies" as opposed to the original `Set-Cookie` header field which was called "Netscape-style cookies".
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] `Set-Cookie2` was seldom used, however, and was deprecated in RFC 6265 in April 2011 which was written as a definitive specification for cookies as used in the real world.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] No modern browser recognizes the `Set-Cookie2` header field.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A *session cookie* (also known as an *in-memory cookie*, *transient cookie* or *non-persistent cookie*) exists only in temporary memory while the user navigates a website.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies expire or are deleted when the user closes the web browser.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies are identified by the browser by the absence of an expiration date assigned to them.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A *persistent cookie* expires at a specific date or after a specific length of time.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] For the persistent cookie's lifespan set by its creator, its information will be transmitted to the server every time the user visits the website that it belongs to, or every time the user views a resource belonging to that website from another website (such as an advertisement).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] For this reason, persistent cookies are sometimes referred to as *tracking cookies* because they can be used by advertisers to record information about a user's web browsing habits over an extended period of time.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Persistent cookies are also used for reasons such as keeping users logged into their accounts on websites, to avoid re-entering login credentials at every visit.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A *secure cookie* can only be transmitted over an encrypted connection (i.e.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] They cannot be transmitted over unencrypted connections (i.e.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This makes the cookie less likely to be exposed to cookie theft via eavesdropping.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A cookie is made secure by adding the `Secure` flag to the cookie.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] An *http-only cookie* cannot be accessed by client-side APIs, such as JavaScript.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This restriction eliminates the threat of cookie theft via cross-site scripting (XSS).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] However, the cookie remains vulnerable to cross-site tracing (XST) and cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A cookie is given this characteristic by adding the `HttpOnly` flag to the cookie.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In 2016 Google Chrome version 51 introduced a new kind of cookie with attribute `SameSite` with possible values of `Strict`, `Lax` or `None`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] With attribute `SameSite=Strict`, the browsers would only send cookies to a target domain that is the same as the origin domain.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This would effectively mitigate cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] With `SameSite=Lax`, browsers would send cookies with requests to a target domain even it is different from the origin domain, but only for *safe* requests such as GET (POST is unsafe) and not third-party cookies (inside iframe).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Attribute `SameSite=None` would allow third-party (cross-site) cookies, however, most browsers require secure attribute on SameSite=None cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The Same-site cookie is incorporated into a new RFC draft for "Cookies: HTTP State Management Mechanism" to update RFC 6265 (if approved).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Chrome, Firefox, and Edge started to support Same-site cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The key of rollout is the treatment of existing cookies without the SameSite attribute defined, Chrome has been treating those existing cookies as if SameSite=None, this would let all website/applications run as before.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Google intended to change that default to `SameSite=Lax` in Chrome 80 planned to be released in February 2020, but due to potential for breakage of those applications/websites that rely on third-party/cross-site cookies and COVID-19 circumstances, Google postponed this change to Chrome 84.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A *supercookie* is a cookie with an origin of a top-level domain (such as `.com`) or a public suffix (such as `.co.uk`).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Ordinary cookies, by contrast, have an origin of a specific domain name, such as `example.com`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Supercookies can be a potential security concern and are therefore often blocked by web browsers.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] If unblocked by the browser, an attacker in control of a malicious website could set a supercookie and potentially disrupt or impersonate legitimate user requests to another website that shares the same top-level domain or public suffix as the malicious website.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] For example, a supercookie with an origin of `.com` could maliciously affect a request made to `example.com`, even if the cookie did not originate from `example.com`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This can be used to fake logins or change user information.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The Public Suffix List helps to mitigate the risk that supercookies pose.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The Public Suffix List is a cross-vendor initiative that aims to provide an accurate and up-to-date list of domain name suffixes.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Older versions of browsers may not have an up-to-date list, and will therefore be vulnerable to supercookies from certain domains.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The term *supercookie* is also used for tracking technologies that do not rely on HTTP cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Two such *supercookie* mechanisms were found on Microsoft websites in August 2011: cookie syncing that respawned MUID (machine unique identifier) cookies, and ETag cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Due to media attention, Microsoft later disabled this code.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In a 2021 blog post, Mozilla used the term *supercookie* to refer to the use of browser cache as a means of tracking users across sites.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Zero or more attributes (name/value pairs).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Attributes store information such as the cookie's expiration, domain, and flags (such as `Secure` and `HttpOnly`).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Cookies were originally introduced to provide a way for users to record items they want to purchase as they navigate throughout a website (a virtual *shopping cart* or *shopping basket*).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Today, however, the contents of a user's shopping cart are usually stored in a database on the server, rather than in a cookie on the client.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] To keep track of which user is assigned to which shopping cart, the server sends a cookie to the client that contains a unique session identifier (typically, a long string of random letters and numbers).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Because cookies are sent to the server with every request the client makes, that session identifier will be sent back to the server every time the user visits a new page on the website, which lets the server know which shopping cart to display to the user.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Another popular use of cookies is for logging into websites.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] When the user visits a website's login page, the web server typically sends the client a cookie containing a unique session identifier.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] When the user successfully logs in, the server remembers that that particular session identifier has been authenticated and grants the user access to its services.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Because session cookies only contain a unique session identifier, this makes the amount of personal information that a website can save about each user virtually limitless—the website is not limited to restrictions concerning how large a cookie can be.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies also help to improve page load times, since the amount of information in a session cookie is small and requires little bandwidth.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can be used to remember information about the user in order to show relevant content to that user over time.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] For example, a web server might send a cookie containing the username that was last used to log into a website, so that it may be filled in automatically the next time the user logs in.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Many websites use cookies for personalization based on the user's preferences.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Users select their preferences by entering them in a web form and submitting the form to the server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The server encodes the preferences in a cookie and sends the cookie back to the browser.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This way, every time the user accesses a page on the website, the server can personalize the page according to the user's preferences.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] For example, the Google search engine once used cookies to allow users (even non-registered ones) to decide how many search results per page they wanted to see.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Also, DuckDuckGo uses cookies to allow users to set the viewing preferences like colors of the web page.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Tracking cookies are used to track users' web browsing habits.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This can also be done to some extent by using the IP address of the computer requesting the page or the referer field of the HTTP request header, but cookies allow for greater precision.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] From this point on, the cookie will automatically be sent by the browser to the server every time a new page from the site is requested.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The server not only sends the page as usual but also stores the URL of the requested page, the date/time of the request, and the cookie in a log file.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] By analyzing this log file, it is then possible to discover which pages the user has visited, in what sequence, and for how long.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Corporations exploit users' web habits by tracking cookies to collect information about buying habits.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The *Wall Street Journal* found that America's top fifty websites installed an average of sixty-four pieces of tracking technology onto computers, resulting in a total of 3,180 tracking files.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The data can then be collected and sold to bidding corporations.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are arbitrary pieces of data, usually chosen and first sent by the web server, and stored on the client computer by the web browser.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The browser then sends them back to the server with every request, introducing states (memory of previous events) into otherwise stateless HTTP transactions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Without cookies, each retrieval of a web page or component of a web page would be an isolated event, largely unrelated to all other page views made by the user on the website.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Although cookies are usually set by the web server, they can also be set by the client using a scripting language such as JavaScript (unless the cookie's `HttpOnly` flag is set, in which case the cookie cannot be modified by scripting languages).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are set using the `Set-Cookie` header field, sent in an HTTP response from the web server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This header field instructs the web browser to store the cookie and send it back in future requests to the server (the browser will ignore this header field if it does not support cookies or has disabled cookies).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The server's HTTP response contains the contents of the website's homepage.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] But it also instructs the browser to set two cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The first, *theme*, is considered to be a *session cookie* since it does not have an `Expires` or `Max-Age` attribute.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies are intended to be deleted by the browser when the browser closes.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The second, *sessionToken*, is considered to be a *persistent cookie* since it contains an `Expires` attribute, which instructs the browser to delete the cookie at a specific date and time.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Next, the browser sends another request to visit the `spec.html` page on the website.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This way, the server knows that this HTTP request is related to the previous one.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The server would answer by sending the requested page, possibly including more `Set-Cookie` header fields in the HTTP response in order to instruct the browser to add new cookies, modify existing cookies, or remove existing cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] To remove a cookie, the server must include a `Set-Cookie` header field with an expiration date in the past.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The value of a cookie may consist of any printable ASCII character (`!` through `~`, Unicode `\u0021` through `\u007E`) excluding `,`and`;` and whitespace characters.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The name of a cookie excludes the same characters, as well as `=`, since that is the delimiter between the name and value.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The cookie standard RFC 2965 is more restrictive but not implemented by browsers.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The term *cookie crumb* is sometimes used to refer to a cookie's name–value pair.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can also be set by scripting languages such as JavaScript that run within the browser.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In JavaScript, the object `document.cookie` is used for this purpose.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] For example, the instruction `document.cookie = "temperature=20"` creates a cookie of name *temperature* and value *20*.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In addition to a name and value, cookies can also have one or more attributes.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Browsers do not include cookie attributes in requests to the server—they only send the cookie's name and value.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Cookie attributes are used by browsers to determine when to delete a cookie, block a cookie or whether to send a cookie to the server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The `Domain` and `Path` attributes define the scope of the cookie.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] They essentially tell the browser what website the cookie belongs to.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] For security reasons, cookies can only be set on the current resource's top domain and its subdomains, and not for another domain and its subdomains.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] For example, the website `example.org` cannot set a cookie that has a domain of `foo.com` because this would allow the website `example.org` to control the cookies of the domain `foo.com`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] If a cookie's `Domain` and `Path` attributes are not specified by the server, they default to the domain and path of the resource that was requested.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] However, in most browsers there is a difference between a cookie set from `foo.com` without a domain, and a cookie set with the `foo.com` domain.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In the former case, the cookie will only be sent for requests to `foo.com`, also known as a host-only cookie.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In the latter case, all subdomains are also included (for example, `docs.foo.com`).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A notable exception to this general rule is Edge prior to Windows 10 RS3 and Internet Explorer prior to IE 11 and Windows 10 RS4 (April 2018), which always sends cookies to subdomains regardless of whether the cookie was set with or without a domain.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Below is an example of some `Set-Cookie` header fields in the HTTP response of a website after a user logged in.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The first cookie, `LSID`, has no `Domain` attribute, and has a `Path` attribute set to `/accounts`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This tells the browser to use the cookie only when requesting pages contained in `docs.foo.com/accounts` (the domain is derived from the request domain).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The other two cookies, `HSID` and `SSID`, would be used when the browser requests any subdomain in `.foo.com` on any path (for example `www.foo.com/bar`).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The prepending dot is optional in recent standards, but can be added for compatibility with RFC 2109 based implementations.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The `Expires` attribute defines a specific date and time for when the browser should delete the cookie.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The date and time are specified in the form `Wdy, DD Mon YYYY HH:MM:SS GMT`, or in the form `Wdy, DD Mon YY HH:MM:SS GMT` for values of YY where YY is greater than or equal to 0 and less than or equal to 69.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Alternatively, the `Max-Age` attribute can be used to set the cookie's expiration as an interval of seconds in the future, relative to the time the browser received the cookie.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The first cookie, `lu`, is set to expire sometime on 15 January 2013.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] It will be used by the client browser until that time.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The second cookie, `made_write_conn`, does not have an expiration date, making it a session cookie.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] It will be deleted after the user closes their browser.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The third cookie, `reg_fb_gate`, has its value changed to *deleted*, with an expiration time in the past.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The browser will delete this cookie right away because its expiration time is in the past.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Note that cookie will only be deleted if the domain and path attributes in the `Set-Cookie` field match the values used when the cookie was created.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] As of 2016 Internet Explorer did not support `Max-Age`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The `Secure` and `HttpOnly` attributes do not have associated values.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Rather, the presence of just their attribute names indicates that their behaviors should be enabled.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The `Secure` attribute is meant to keep cookie communication limited to encrypted transmission, directing browsers to use cookies only via secure/encrypted connections.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] However, if a web server sets a cookie with a secure attribute from a non-secure connection, the cookie can still be intercepted when it is sent to the user by man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Therefore, for maximum security, cookies with the Secure attribute should only be set over a secure connection.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The `HttpOnly` attribute directs browsers not to expose cookies through channels other than HTTP (and HTTPS) requests.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This means that the cookie cannot be accessed via client-side scripting languages (notably JavaScript), and therefore cannot be stolen easily via cross-site scripting (a pervasive attack technique).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Most modern browsers support cookies and allow the user to disable them.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Add-on tools for managing cookie permissions also exist.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Cookies have some important implications for the privacy and anonymity of web users.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] While cookies are sent only to the server setting them or a server in the same Internet domain, a web page may contain images or other components stored on servers in other domains.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Cookies that are set during retrieval of these components are called *third-party cookies*.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A third-party cookie, belongs to a domain different from the one shown in the address bar.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This sort of cookie typically appears when web pages feature content from external websites, such as banner advertisements.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This opens up the potential for tracking the user's browsing history and is used by advertisers to serve relevant advertisements to each user.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] As an example, suppose a user visits `www.example.org`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This website contains an advertisement from `ad.foxytracking.com`, which, when downloaded, sets a cookie belonging to the advertisement's domain (`ad.foxytracking.com`).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Then, the user visits another website, `www.foo.com`, which also contains an advertisement from `ad.foxytracking.com` and sets a cookie belonging to that domain (`ad.foxytracking.com`).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Eventually, both of these cookies will be sent to the advertiser when loading their advertisements or visiting their website.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The advertiser can then use these cookies to build up a browsing history of the user across all the websites that have ads from this advertiser, through the use of the HTTP referer header field.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] As of 2014, some websites were setting cookies readable for over 100 third-party domains.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] On average, a single website was setting 10 cookies, with a maximum number of cookies (first- and third-party) reaching over 800.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The older standards for cookies, RFC 2109 and RFC 2965, recommend that browsers should protect user privacy and not allow sharing of cookies between servers by default.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] However, the newer standard, RFC 6265, explicitly allows user agents to implement whichever third-party cookie policy they wish.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Most modern web browsers contain privacy settings that can block third-party cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Since 2020, Apple Safari, Firefox, and Brave block all third-party cookies by default.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Safari allows embedded sites to use Storage Access API to request permission to set first-party cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In May 2020, Google Chrome 83 introduced new features to block third-party cookies by default in its Incognito mode for private browsing, making blocking optional during normal browsing.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The same update also added an option to block first-party cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In April 2024, Chrome postponed third-party cookie blocking by default to 2025.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In July 2024, Google announced plan to avoid blocking third-party cookies by default and instead prompt users to allow third-party cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The possibility of building a profile of users is a privacy threat, especially when tracking is done across multiple domains using third-party cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] For this reason, some countries have legislation about cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Website operators who do not disclose third-party cookie use to consumers run the risk of harming consumer trust if cookie use is discovered.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Having clear disclosure (such as in a privacy policy) tends to eliminate any negative effects of such cookie discovery.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The government of the United States set strict rules on setting cookies in 2000 after it was disclosed that the White House drug policy office used cookies to track computer users viewing its online anti-drug advertising.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In 2002, privacy activist Daniel Brandt found that the CIA had been leaving persistent cookies on computers that had visited its website.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] When notified it was violating policy, CIA stated that these cookies were not intentionally set and stopped setting them.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] On 25 December 2005, Brandt discovered that the National Security Agency (NSA) had been leaving two persistent cookies on visitors' computers due to a software upgrade.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] After being informed, the NSA immediately disabled the cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In 2002, the European Union launched the Directive on Privacy and Electronic Communications (e-Privacy Directive), a policy requiring end users' consent for the placement of cookies, and similar technologies for storing and accessing information on users' equipment.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In particular, Article 5 Paragraph 3 mandates that storing technically unnecessary data on a user's computer can only be done if the user is provided information about how this data is used, and the user is given the possibility of denying this storage operation.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The Directive does not require users to authorise or be provided notice of cookie usage that are functionally required for delivering a service they have requested, for example to retain settings, store log-in sessions, or remember what is in a user's shopping basket.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In 2009, the law was amended by Directive 2009/136/EC, which included a change to Article 5, Paragraph 3.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Instead of having an option for users to opt out of cookie storage, the revised Directive requires consent to be obtained for cookie storage.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The definition of consent is cross-referenced to the definition in European data protection law, firstly the Data Protection Directive 1995 and subsequently the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] As the definition of consent was strengthened in the text of the GDPR, this increased the quality of consent required by those storing and accessing information such as cookies on users devices.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In a case decided under the Data Protection Directive however, the Court of Justice of the European Union later confirmed however that the previous law implied the same strong quality of consent as the current instrument.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In addition to the requirement of consent which stems from storing or accessing information on a user's terminal device, the information in many cookies will be considered personal data under the GDPR alone, and will require a legal basis to process.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This has been the case since the 1995 Data Protection Directive, which used an identical definition of personal data, although the GDPR in interpretative Recital 30 clarifies that cookie identifiers are included.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] While not all data processing under the GDPR requires consent, the characteristics of behavioural advertising mean that it is difficult or impossible to justify under any other ground.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Consent under the combination of the GDPR and e-Privacy Directive has to meet a number of conditions in relation to cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] It must be freely given and unambiguous: preticked boxes were banned under both the Data Protection Directive 1995 and the GDPR (Recital 32).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The GDPR is specific that consent must be as 'easy to withdraw as to give', meaning that a reject-all button must be as easy to access in terms of clicks and visibility as an 'accept all' button.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] It must be specific and informed, meaning that consent relates to particular purposes for the use of this data, and all organisations seeking to use this consent must be specifically named.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The Court of Justice of the European Union has also ruled that consent must be 'efficient and timely', meaning that it must be gained before cookies are laid and data processing begins instead of afterwards.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The industry's response has been largely negative.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Robert Bond of the law firm Speechly Bircham describes the effects as "far-reaching and incredibly onerous" for "all UK companies".
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Simon Davis of Privacy International argues that proper enforcement would "destroy the entire industry".
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] However, scholars note that the onerous nature of cookie pop-ups stems from an attempt to continue to operate a business model through convoluted requests that may be incompatible with the GDPR.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Academic studies and regulators both describe widespread non-compliance with the law.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A study scraping 10,000 UK websites found that only 11.8% of sites adhered to minimal legal requirements, with only 33.4% of websites studied providing a mechanism to reject cookies that was as easy to use as accepting them.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A study of 17,000 websites found that 84% of sites breached this criterion, finding additionally that many laid third party cookies with no notice at all.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A W3C specification called P3P was proposed for servers to communicate their privacy policy to browsers, allowing automatic, user-configurable handling.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] However, few websites implement the specification, and the W3C has discontinued work on the specification.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Third-party cookies can be blocked by most browsers to increase privacy and reduce tracking by advertising and tracking companies without negatively affecting the user's web experience on all sites.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Some sites operate 'cookie walls', which make access to a site conditional on allowing cookies either technically in a browser, through pressing 'accept', or both.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In 2020, the European Data Protection Board, composed of all EU data protection regulators, stated that cookie walls were illegal.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Many advertising operators have an opt-out option to behavioural advertising, with a generic cookie in the browser stopping behavioural advertising.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] However, this is often ineffective against many forms of tracking, such as first-party tracking that is growing in popularity to avoid the impact of browsers blocking third party cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Furthermore, if such a setting is more difficult to place than the acceptance of tracking, it remains in breach of the conditions of the e-Privacy Directive.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Most websites use cookies as the only identifiers for user sessions, because other methods of identifying web users have limitations and vulnerabilities.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] If a website uses cookies as session identifiers, attackers can impersonate users' requests by stealing a full set of victims' cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] From the web server's point of view, a request from an attacker then has the same authentication as the victim's requests; thus the request is performed on behalf of the victim's session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Listed here are various scenarios of cookie theft and user session hijacking (even without stealing user cookies) that work with websites relying solely on HTTP cookies for user identification.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Traffic on a network can be intercepted and read by computers on the network other than the sender and receiver (particularly over unencrypted open Wi-Fi).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This traffic includes cookies sent on ordinary unencrypted HTTP sessions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Where network traffic is not encrypted, attackers can therefore read the communications of other users on the network, including HTTP cookies as well as the entire contents of the conversations, for the purpose of a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] An attacker could use intercepted cookies to impersonate a user and perform a malicious task, such as transferring money out of the victim's bank account.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This issue can be resolved by securing the communication between the user's computer and the server by employing Transport Layer Security (HTTPS protocol) to encrypt the connection.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] A server can specify the `Secure` flag while setting a cookie, which will cause the browser to send the cookie only over an encrypted channel, such as a TLS connection.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] If an attacker is able to cause a DNS server to cache a fabricated DNS entry (called DNS cache poisoning), then this could allow the attacker to gain access to a user's cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] For example, an attacker could use DNS cache poisoning to create a fabricated DNS entry of `f12345.www.example.com` that points to the IP address of the attacker's server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The attacker can then post an image URL from his own server (for example, `http://f12345.www.example.com/img_4_cookie.jpg`).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Victims reading the attacker's message would download this image from `f12345.www.example.com`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Since `f12345.www.example.com` is a sub-domain of `www.example.com`, victims' browsers would submit all `example.com`-related cookies to the attacker's server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] If an attacker is able to accomplish this, it is usually the fault of the Internet service providers for not properly securing their DNS servers.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] However, the severity of this attack can be lessened if the target website uses secure cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In this case, the attacker would have the extra challenge of obtaining the target website's TLS certificate from a certificate authority, since secure cookies can only be transmitted over an encrypted connection.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Without a matching TLS certificate, victims' browsers would display a warning message about the attacker's invalid certificate, which would help deter users from visiting the attacker's fraudulent website and sending the attacker their cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can also be stolen using a technique called cross-site scripting.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This occurs when an attacker takes advantage of a website that allows its users to post unfiltered HTML and JavaScript content.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] By posting malicious HTML and JavaScript code, the attacker can cause the victim's web browser to send the victim's cookies to a website the attacker controls.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] When another user clicks on this link, the browser executes the piece of code within the `onclick` attribute, thus replacing the string `document.cookie` with the list of cookies that are accessible from the current page.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] As a result, this list of cookies is sent to the `attacker.com` server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] If the attacker's malicious posting is on an HTTPS website `https://www.example.com`, secure cookies will also be sent to attacker.com in plain text.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] It is the responsibility of the website developers to filter out such malicious code.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Such attacks can be mitigated by using HttpOnly cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] These cookies will not be accessible by client-side scripting languages like JavaScript, and therefore, the attacker will not be able to gather these cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In older versions of many browsers, there were security holes in the implementation of the XMLHttpRequest API.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This API allows pages to specify a proxy server that would get the reply, and this proxy server is not subject to the same-origin policy.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] For example, a victim is reading an attacker's posting on `www.example.com`, and the attacker's script is executed in the victim's browser.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] The script generates a request to `www.example.com` with the proxy server `attacker.com`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Since the request is for `www.example.com`, all `example.com` cookies will be sent along with the request, but routed through the attacker's proxy server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Hence, the attacker would be able to harvest the victim's cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] This attack would not work with secure cookies, since they can only be transmitted over HTTPS connections, and the HTTPS protocol dictates end-to-end encryption (i.e. the information is encrypted on the user's browser and decrypted on the destination server).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In this case, the proxy server would only see the raw, encrypted bytes of the HTTP request.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] For example, Bob might be browsing a chat forum where another user, Mallory, has posted a message.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] If Bob's bank keeps his authentication information in a cookie, and if the cookie hasn't expired, then the attempt by Bob's browser to load the image will submit the withdrawal form with his cookie, thus authorizing a transaction without Bob's approval.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Besides privacy concerns, cookies also have some technical drawbacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] In particular, they do not always accurately identify users, they can be used for security attacks, and they are often at odds with the Representational State Transfer (REST) software architectural style.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] If more than one browser is used on a computer, each usually has a separate storage area for cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Hence, cookies do not identify a person, but a combination of a user account, a computer, and a web browser.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Thus, anyone who uses multiple accounts, computers, or browsers has multiple sets of cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p01] Likewise, cookies do not differentiate between multiple users who share the same user account, computer, and browser.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Some of the operations that can be done using cookies can also be done using other mechanisms.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] A JSON Web Token (JWT) is a self-contained packet of information that can be used to store user identity and authenticity information.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] This allows them to be used in place of session cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Unlike cookies, which are automatically attached to each HTTP request by the browser, JWTs must be explicitly attached to each HTTP request by the web application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] The HTTP protocol includes the basic access authentication and the digest access authentication protocols, which allow access to a web page only when the user has provided the correct username and password.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] If the server requires such credentials for granting access to a web page, the browser requests them from the user and, once obtained, the browser stores and sends them in every subsequent page request.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] This information can be used to track the user.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] The query string part of the URL is the part that is typically used for this purpose, but other parts can be used as well.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] The Java Servlet and PHP session mechanisms both use this method if cookies are not enabled.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] This method consists of the web server appending query strings containing a unique session identifier to all the links inside of a web page.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] When the user follows a link, the browser sends the query string to the server, allowing the server to identify the user and maintain state.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] These kinds of query strings are very similar to cookies in that both contain arbitrary pieces of information chosen by the server and both are sent back to the server on every request.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Since a query string is part of a URL, if that URL is later reused, the same attached piece of information will be sent to the server, which could lead to confusion.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] For example, if the preferences of a user are encoded in the query string of a URL and the user sends this URL to another user by e-mail, those preferences will be used for that other user as well.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Moreover, if the same user accesses the same page multiple times from different sources, there is no guarantee that the same query string will be used each time.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] For example, if a user visits a page by coming from a page *internal to the site* the first time, and then visits the same page by coming from an *external search engine* the second time, the query strings would likely be different.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] If cookies were used in this situation, the cookies would be the same.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Other drawbacks of query strings are related to security.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Storing data that identifies a session in a query string enables session fixation attacks, referer logging attacks and other security exploits.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Transferring session identifiers as HTTP cookies is more secure.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Another form of session tracking is to use web forms with hidden fields.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] This technique is very similar to using URL query strings to hold the information and has many of the same advantages and drawbacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] In fact, if the form is handled with the HTTP GET method, then this technique is similar to using URL query strings, since the GET method adds the form fields to the URL as a query string.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] But most forms are handled with HTTP POST, which causes the form information, including the hidden fields, to be sent in the HTTP request body, which is neither part of the URL, nor of a cookie.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] This approach presents two advantages from the point of view of the tracker.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] First, having the tracking information placed in the HTTP request body rather than in the URL means it will not be noticed by the average user.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Second, the session information is not copied when the user copies the URL (to bookmark the page or send it via email, for example).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] All current web browsers can store a fairly large amount of data (2–32 MB) via JavaScript using the DOM property `window.name`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] This data can be used instead of session cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] The technique can be coupled with JSON/JavaScript objects to store complex sets of session variables on the client side.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] The downside is that every separate window or tab will initially have an empty `window.name` property when opened.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] In some respects, this can be more secure than cookies because its contents are not automatically sent to the server on every request like cookies are, so it is not vulnerable to network cookie sniffing attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Some users may be tracked based on the IP address of the computer requesting the page.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] The server knows the IP address of the computer running the browser (or the proxy, if any is used) and could theoretically link a user's session to this IP address.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] However, IP addresses are generally not a reliable way to track a session or identify a user.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Many computers designed to be used by a single user, such as office PCs or home PCs, are behind a network address translator (NAT).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] This means that several PCs will share a public IP address.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Furthermore, some systems, such as Tor, are designed to retain Internet anonymity, rendering tracking by IP address impractical, impossible, or a security risk.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Because ETags are cached by the browser, and returned with subsequent requests for the same resource, a tracking server can simply repeat any ETag received from the browser to ensure an assigned ETag persists indefinitely (in a similar way to persistent cookies).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Additional caching header fields can also enhance the preservation of ETag data.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] ETags can be flushed in some browsers by clearing the browser cache.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] The browser cache can also be used to store information that can be used to track individual users.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] This technique takes advantage of the fact that the web browser will use resources stored within the cache instead of downloading them from the website when it determines that the cache already has the most up-to-date version of the resource.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] For example, a website could serve a JavaScript file with code that sets a unique identifier for the user (for example, `var userId = 3243242;`).
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] After the user's initial visit, every time the user accesses the page, this file will be loaded from the cache instead of downloaded from the server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] A browser fingerprint is information collected about a browser's configuration, such as version number, screen resolution, and operating system, for the purpose of identification.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Fingerprints can be used to fully or partially identify individual users or devices even when cookies are turned off.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Basic web browser configuration information has long been collected by web analytics services in an effort to accurately measure real human web traffic and discount various forms of click fraud.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] With the assistance of client-side scripting languages, collection of much more esoteric parameters is possible.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Assimilation of such information into a single string constitutes a device fingerprint.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] In 2010, EFF measured at least 18.1 bits of entropy possible from browser fingerprinting.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Canvas fingerprinting, a more recent technique, claims to add another 5.7 bits.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Some web browsers support persistence mechanisms which allow the page to store the information locally for later use.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] The HTML5 standard (which most modern web browsers support to some extent) includes a JavaScript API called Web storage that allows two types of storage: local storage and session storage.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Local storage behaves similarly to persistent cookies while session storage behaves similarly to session cookies, except that session storage is tied to an individual tab/window's lifetime (AKA a page session), not to a whole browser session like session cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Internet Explorer supports persistent information in the browser's history, in the browser's favorites, in an XML store ("user data"), or directly within a web page saved to disk.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] Some web browser plugins include persistence mechanisms as well.
[src:session-fixation-defense/http-cookie-p02] For example, Adobe Flash has Local shared object and Microsoft Silverlight has Isolated storage.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Usage of MFA has increased in recent years.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Security issues which can cause the bypass of MFA are fatigue attacks, phishing and SIM swapping.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Accounts with MFA enabled are significantly less likely to be compromised.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Authentication takes place when someone tries to log into a computer resource (such as a computer network, device, or application).
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] The resource requires the user to supply the identity by which the user is known to the resource, along with evidence of the authenticity of the user's claim to that identity.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Simple authentication requires only one such piece of evidence (factor), typically a password, or occasionally multiple pieces of evidence all of the same type, as with a credit card number and a card verification code (CVC).
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] For additional security, the resource may require more than one factor—multi-factor authentication, or two-factor authentication in cases where exactly two types of evidence are to be supplied.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] The use of multiple authentication factors to prove one's identity is based on the premise that an unauthorized actor is unlikely to be able to supply all of the factors required for access.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] If, in an authentication attempt, at least one of the components is missing or supplied incorrectly, the user's identity is not established with sufficient certainty and access to the asset (e.g., a building, or data) being protected by multi-factor authentication then remains blocked.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] An example of two-factor authentication is the withdrawing of money from an ATM; only the correct combination of a physically present bank card (something the user possesses) and a PIN (something the user knows) allows the transaction to be carried out.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Two other examples are to supplement a user-controlled password with a one-time password (OTP) or code generated or received by an authenticator (e.g. a security token or smartphone) that only the user possesses.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] An authenticator app enables two-factor authentication in a different way, by showing a randomly generated and constantly refreshing code, rather than sending an SMS or using another method.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] This code is a Time-based one-time password (a *TOTP*), and the authenticator app contains the key material that allows the generation of these codes.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Knowledge factors ("something only the user knows") are a form of authentication.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In this form, the user is required to prove knowledge of a secret in order to authenticate.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] A password is a secret word or string of characters that is used for user authentication.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] This is the most commonly used mechanism of authentication.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication techniques rely on passwords as one factor of authentication.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Variations include both longer ones formed from multiple words (a passphrase) and the shorter, purely numeric, PIN commonly used for ATM access.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Traditionally, passwords are expected to be memorized, but can also be written down on a hidden paper or text file.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Possession factors ("something only the user has") have been used for authentication for centuries, in the form of a key to a lock.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] The basic principle is that the key embodies a secret that is shared between the lock and the key, and the same principle underlies possession factor authentication in computer systems.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] A security token is an example of a possession factor.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] *soft token*) is a type of two-factor authentication security device that may be used to authorize the use of computer services.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] A soft token may not be a device the user interacts with.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Typically an X.509v3 certificate is loaded onto the device and stored securely to serve this purpose.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Inherent factors ("something the user is"), are factors associated with the user, and are usually biometric methods, including fingerprint, face, voice, or iris recognition.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Behavioral biometrics such as keystroke dynamics can also be used.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Increasingly, a fourth factor is coming into play involving the physical location of the user.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] While hard wired to the corporate network, a user could be allowed to login using only a pin code, whereas if the user was working remotely, a more secure MFA method such as entering a code from a soft token as well could be required.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Adapting the type of MFA method and frequency to a users' location will enable the avoidance of risks common to remote working.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Systems for network admission control work in similar ways where the level of network access can be contingent on the specific network a device is connected to, such as Wi-Fi vs wired connectivity.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] This also allows a user to move between offices and dynamically receive the same level of network access in each.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Two-factor authentication over text message was developed as early as 1996, when AT&T described a system for authorizing transactions based on an exchange of codes over two-way pagers.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication vendors offer mobile phone-based authentication.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Some methods include push-based authentication, QR code-based authentication, one-time password authentication (event-based and time-based), and SMS-based verification.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] SMS-based verification suffers from some security concerns.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Phones can be cloned, apps can run on several phones and cell-phone maintenance personnel can read SMS texts.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Not least, cell phones can be compromised in general, meaning the phone is no longer something only the user has.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] The major drawback of authentication including something the user possesses is that the user must carry around the physical token (the USB stick, the bank card, the key or similar), practically at all times.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Many organizations forbid carrying USB and electronic devices in or out of premises owing to malware and data theft risks, and most important machines do not have USB ports for the same reason.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Physical tokens usually do not scale, typically requiring a new token for each new account and system.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Procuring and subsequently replacing tokens of this kind involves costs.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In addition, there are inherent conflicts and unavoidable trade-offs between usability and security.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Two-step authentication involving mobile phones and smartphones provides an alternative to dedicated physical devices.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] To authenticate, people can use their personal access codes to the device (i.e. something that only the individual user knows) plus a one-time-valid, dynamic passcode, typically consisting of 4 to 6 digits.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] The passcode can be sent to their mobile device by SMS or can be generated by a one-time passcode-generator app.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In both cases, the advantage of using a mobile phone is that there is no need for an additional dedicated token, as users tend to carry their mobile devices around at all times.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Notwithstanding the popularity of SMS verification, security advocates have publicly criticized SMS verification, and in July 2016, a United States NIST draft guideline proposed deprecating it as a form of authentication.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] A year later NIST reinstated SMS verification as a valid authentication channel in the finalized guideline.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] As early as 2011, Duo Security was offering push notifications for MFA via a mobile app.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In 2016 and 2017 respectively, both Google and Apple started offering user two-step authentication with push notifications as an alternative method.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Security of SMS-delivered security tokens fully depends on the mobile operator's operational security and can be easily breached by wiretapping or SIM cloning by national security agencies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] The Payment Card Industry (PCI) Data Security Standard, requirement 8.3, requires the use of MFA for all remote network access that originates from outside the network to a Card Data Environment (CDE).
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Beginning with PCI-DSS version 3.2, the use of MFA is required for all administrative access to the CDE, even if the user is within a trusted network.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] The second Payment Services Directive requires "strong customer authentication" on most electronic payments in the European Economic Area since September 14, 2019.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In India, the Reserve Bank of India mandated two-factor authentication for all online transactions made using a debit or credit card using either a password or a one-time password sent over SMS.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] This requirement was removed in 2016 for transactions up to ₹2,000 after opting-in with the issuing bank.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Vendors such as Uber have been mandated by the bank to amend their payment processing systems in compliance with this two-factor authentication rollout.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Details for authentication for federal employees and contractors in the U.S. are defined in Homeland Security Presidential Directive 12 (HSPD-12).
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] IT regulatory standards for access to federal government systems require the use of multi-factor authentication to access sensitive IT resources, for example when logging on to network devices to perform administrative tasks and when accessing any computer using a privileged login.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] NIST Special Publication 800-63-3 discusses various forms of two-factor authentication and provides guidance on using them in business processes requiring different levels of assurance.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In response to the publication, numerous authentication vendors began improperly promoting challenge-questions, secret images, and other knowledge-based methods as "multi-factor" authentication.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Considering the reliability of the method, in some countries, MFA is obligatory in certain industries, such as healthcare, to prevent the theft of sensitive information.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In the healthcare sector, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule has historically listed access controls as a required implementation specification but did not explicitly mandate multi-factor authentication.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] The HHS Office for Civil Rights noted in enforcement guidance that the lack of MFA was a contributing factor in multiple healthcare data breaches investigated under HIPAA.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In December 2024, HHS published a Notice of Proposed Rulemaking that would make multi-factor authentication a mandatory requirement for all HIPAA-regulated entities accessing electronic protected health information.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] According to proponents, multi-factor authentication could drastically reduce the incidence of online identity theft and other online fraud, because the victim's password would no longer be enough to give a thief permanent access to their information.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] However, many multi-factor authentication approaches remain vulnerable to phishing, man-in-the-browser, and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] To counter phishing attacks, users should not share their verification codes with anyone, and many web application providers will place an advisory in an e-mail or SMS containing a code.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In May 2017, O2 Telefónica, a German mobile service provider, confirmed that cybercriminals had exploited SS7 vulnerabilities to bypass SMS based two-step authentication to do unauthorized withdrawals from users' bank accounts.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] The criminals first infected the account holder's computers in an attempt to steal their bank account credentials and phone numbers.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Then the attackers purchased access to a fake telecom provider and set up a redirect for the victim's phone number to a handset controlled by them.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Finally, the attackers logged into victims' online bank accounts and requested for the money on the accounts to be withdrawn to accounts owned by the criminals.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] SMS passcodes were routed to phone numbers controlled by the attackers and the criminals transferred the money out.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] An increasingly common approach to defeating MFA is to bombard the user with many requests to accept a log-in, until the user eventually succumbs to the volume of requests and by mistake accepts one.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] This form of social engineering is called *multi-factor authentication fatigue attack* (also MFA fatigue attack or MFA bombing), and may include other elements, such as calls pretending to be from IT support.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] When MFA applications are configured to send push notifications to end users, an attacker can send a flood of login attempts in the hope that a user will click on accept at least once.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In 2022, Microsoft deployed a mitigation against MFA fatigue attacks with their authenticator app, by optionally requiring the user to type in a number in addition to clicking "approve".
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In September 2022 Uber security was breached by a member of Lapsus$ using a multi-factor fatigue attack.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In early 2024, a small percentage of Apple consumers experienced a MFA fatigue attack that was caused by a hacker that bypassed the rate limit and Captcha on Apple’s “Forgot Password” page.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication products require users to deploy client software to make multi-factor authentication systems work.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Some vendors have created separate installation packages for network login, Web access credentials, and VPN connection credentials.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] For such products, there may be four or five different software packages to push down to the client PC in order to make use of the token or smart card.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] This translates to four or five packages on which version control has to be performed, and four or five packages to check for conflicts with business applications.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] If access can be operated using web pages, it is possible to limit the overheads outlined above to a single application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] With other multi-factor authentication technology such as hardware token products, no software must be installed by end-users.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Some studies have shown that poorly implemented MFA recovery procedures can introduce new vulnerabilities that attackers may exploit.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] There are drawbacks to multi-factor authentication that are keeping many approaches from becoming widespread.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Some users have difficulty keeping track of a hardware token or USB plug.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Many users do not have the technical skills needed to install a client-side software certificate by themselves.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Generally, multi-factor solutions require additional investment for implementation and costs for maintenance.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Most hardware token-based systems are proprietary, and some vendors charge an annual fee per user.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Deployment of hardware tokens is logistically challenging.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Hardware tokens may get damaged or lost, and issuance of tokens in large industries such as banking or even within large enterprises needs to be managed.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In addition to deployment costs, multi-factor authentication often carries significant additional support costs.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] A 2008 survey of over 120 U.S. credit unions by the *Credit Union Journal* reported on the support costs associated with two-factor authentication.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In their report, software certificates and software toolbar approaches were reported to have the highest support costs.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] Research into deployments of multi-factor authentication schemes has shown that one of the elements that tend to impact the adoption of such systems is the line of business of the organization that deploys the multi-factor authentication system.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] While the perception is that multi-factor authentication is within the realm of perfect security, Roger Grimes writes that if not properly implemented and configured, multi-factor authentication can in fact be easily defeated.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] In 2013, Kim Dotcom claimed to have invented two-factor authentication in a 2000 patent, and briefly threatened to sue all the major web services.
[src:session-fixation-defense/multi-factor-authentication] However, the European Patent Office revoked his patent in light of an earlier 1998 U.S. patent held by AT&T.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] A session is established at a certain point in time, and then ‘torn down’ - brought to an end - at some later point.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] An established communication session may involve more than one message in each direction.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] An established session is the basic requirement to perform a connection-oriented communication.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] A session also is the basic step to transmit in connectionless communication modes.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] However, any unidirectional transmission does not define a session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] In the case of transport protocols that do not implement a formal session layer (e.g., UDP) or where sessions at the application layer are generally very short-lived (e.g., HTTP), sessions are maintained by a higher level program using a method defined in the data being exchanged.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] For example, an HTTP exchange between a browser and a remote host may include an HTTP cookie which identifies state, such as a unique session ID, information about the user's preferences or authorization level.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] HTTP/1.0 was thought to only allow a single request and response during one Web/HTTP Session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Protocol version HTTP/1.1 improved this by completing the Common Gateway Interface (CGI), making it easier to maintain the Web Session and supporting HTTP cookies and file uploads.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Most client-server sessions are maintained by the transport layer - a single connection for a single session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] However each transaction phase of a Web/HTTP session creates a separate connection.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Maintaining session continuity between phases requires a session ID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] The session ID is embedded within the `<A HREF>` or `<FORM>` links of dynamic web pages so that it is passed back to the CGI.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] CGI then uses the session ID to ensure session continuity between transaction phases.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] One advantage of one connection-per-phase is that it works well over low bandwidth (modem) connections.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] TCP sessions are typically implemented in software using child processes and/or multithreading, where a new process or thread is created when the computer establishes or joins a session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] HTTP sessions are typically not implemented using one thread per session, but by means of a database with information about the state of each session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] The advantage with multiple processes or threads is relaxed complexity of the software, since each thread is an instance with its own history and encapsulated variables.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] The disadvantage is large overhead in terms of system resources, and that the session may be interrupted if the system is restarted.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] When a client may connect to any server in a cluster of servers, a special problem is encountered in maintaining consistency when the servers must maintain session state.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] The client must either be directed to the same server for the duration of the session, or the servers must transmit server-side session information via a shared file system or database.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Otherwise, the client may reconnect to a different server than the one it started the session with, which will cause problems when the new server does not have access to the stored state of the old one.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Server-side sessions are handy and efficient, but can become difficult to handle in conjunction with load-balancing/high-availability systems and are not usable at all in some embedded systems with no storage.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] The load-balancing problem can be solved by using shared storage or by applying forced peering between each client and a single server in the cluster, although this can compromise system efficiency and load distribution.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] A method of using server-side sessions in systems without mass-storage is to reserve a portion of RAM for storage of session data.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] This method is applicable for servers with a limited number of clients (e.g. router or access point with infrequent or disallowed access to more than one client at a time).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Client-side sessions use cookies and cryptographic techniques to maintain state without storing as much data on the server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] When presenting a dynamic web page, the server sends the current state data to the client (web browser) in the form of a cookie.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] The client saves the cookie in memory or on disk.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] With each successive request, the client sends the cookie back to the server, and the server uses the data to "remember" the state of the application for that specific client and generate an appropriate response.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] This mechanism may work well in some contexts; however, data stored on the client is vulnerable to tampering by the user or by software that has access to the client computer.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Data integrity: Nothing apart from the server should manipulate session data (accidentally or maliciously).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Authenticity: Nothing apart from the server should be able to initiate valid sessions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] To accomplish this, the server needs to encrypt the session data before sending it to the client, and modification of such information by any other party should be prevented via cryptographic means.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Transmitting state back and forth with every request is only practical when the size of the cookie is small.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] In essence, client-side sessions trade server disk space for the extra bandwidth that each web request will require.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Moreover, web browsers limit the number and size of cookies that may be stored by a web site.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] To improve efficiency and allow for more session data, the server may compress the data before creating the cookie, decompressing it later when the cookie is returned by the client.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] A session token is a unique identifier that is generated and sent from a server to a client to identify the current interaction session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] The client usually stores and sends the token as an HTTP cookie and/or sends it as a parameter in GET or POST queries.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] The reason to use session tokens is that the client only has to handle the identifier—all session data is stored on the server (usually in a database, to which the client does not have direct access) linked to that identifier.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Examples of the names that some programming languages use when naming their HTTP cookie include JSESSIONID (JSP), PHPSESSID (PHP), CGISESSID (CGI), and ASPSESSIONID (ASP).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] In human–computer interaction, **session management** is the process of keeping track of a user's activity across sessions of interaction with the computer system.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Typical session management tasks in a desktop environment include keeping track of which applications are open and which documents each application has opened, so that the same state can be restored when the user logs out and logs in later.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] For a website, session management might involve requiring the user to re-login if the session has expired (i.e., a certain time limit has passed without user activity).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] It is also used to store information on the server-side between HTTP requests.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] A desktop session manager is a program that can save and restore desktop sessions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] A desktop session is all the windows currently running and their current content.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Session management on Linux-based systems is provided by X session manager.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] On Microsoft Windows systems, session management is provided by the Session Manager Subsystem (smss.exe); user session functionality can be extended by third-party applications like twinsplay.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Session management is particularly useful in a web browser where a user can save all open pages and settings and restore them at a later date or on a different computer (see data portability).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] To help recover from a system or application crash, pages and settings can also be restored on next run.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Internet Explorer, OmniWeb and Opera are examples of web browsers that support session management.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Session management is often managed through the application of cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) is stateless.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Session management is the technique used by the web developer to make the stateless HTTP protocol support session state.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] For example, once a user has been authenticated to the web server, the user's next HTTP request (GET or POST) should not cause the web server to ask for the user's account and password again.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] In situations where multiple web servers must share knowledge of session state (as is typical in a cluster environment) session information must be shared between the cluster nodes that are running web server software.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] However, if session information is subject to audit compliance, consideration should be given to the method used for session storage, replication, and clustering.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] In a service-oriented architecture, Simple Object Access Protocol or SOAP messages constructed with Extensible Markup Language (XML) messages can be used by consumer applications to cause web servers to create sessions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Just as HTTP is a stateless protocol, so is SMS.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] As SMS became interoperable across rival networks in 1999, and text messaging started its ascent towards becoming a ubiquitous global form of communication, various enterprises became interested in using the SMS channel for commercial purposes.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Initial services did not require session management since they were only one-way communications (for example, in 2000, the first mobile news service was delivered via SMS in Finland).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] Today, these applications are referred to as application-to-peer (A2P) messaging as distinct from peer-to-peer (P2P) messaging.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-computer-science] The development of interactive enterprise applications required session management, but because SMS is a stateless protocol as defined by the GSM standards, early implementations were controlled client-side by having the end-users enter commands and service identifiers manually.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] In computer network security, **session fixation attacks** attempt to exploit the vulnerability of a system that allows one person to fixate (find or set) another person's session identifier.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Most session fixation attacks are web based, and most rely on session identifiers being accepted from URLs (query string) or POST data.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Mallory intends to target Alice's money from her bank.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Alice has a reasonable level of trust in Mallory, and will visit links Mallory sends her.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Mallory sends Alice an e-mail: "Hey, check this out, there is a cool new account summary feature on our bank, `http://unsafe.example.com/?SID=I_WILL_KNOW_THE_SID`".
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Mallory is trying to fixate the SID to `I_WILL_KNOW_THE_SID`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Alice is interested and visits `http://unsafe.example.com/?SID=I_WILL_KNOW_THE_SID`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] The usual log-on screen pops up, and Alice logs on.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Mallory visits `http://unsafe.example.com/?SID=I_WILL_KNOW_THE_SID` and now has unlimited access to Alice's account.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] A misconception is that if a server only accepts server-generated session identifiers, it is safe from fixation.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Alice logs on, with fixated session identifier `SID=0D6441FEA4496C2`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Mallory visits `http://vulnerable.example.com/?SID=0D6441FEA4496C2` and now has unlimited access to Alice's account.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] This type of attack is similar to a cross-site cookie attack except that, it does not rely on the vulnerability of the user's browser.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Rather, it relies on the fact that wildcard cookies can be set by a subdomain and, that those cookies may affect other subdomains.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] When Alice visits `www.example.com` this cookie will be sent with the request and Alice will have the session specified by Mallory's cookie.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] If Alice now logs on, Mallory can use her account.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] When this attack is complete, Mallory can gain access to `www.example.com` as Alice.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] It is not essential that a user login to exploit session fixation attacks and, although these unauthenticated attacks are not constrained to cross-sub-domain cookie attacks, the implications of sub-domain attacks are relevant to these unauthenticated scenarios.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] For example, Mallory may provide a URL from their evil site, fixating a session into an unauthenticated scenario, and use those techniques to exploit their target.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] This includes scenarios exploiting both the unauthenticated scenarios (e.g. forms or registration) as well as the ability to feed the user an established session to bypass the login completely.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Consider, for example, that Mallory may create a user *A1ice* on *www.example.com* and login that user to capture a current, valid session identifier.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Mallory then entraps Alice with a URL from *evil.example.com* which fixates that session cookie in Alice's browser (as described above) and redirects to *www.example.com* for finalizing a particular transaction (or, in fact, broader use).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Mallory is thus able to ghost the session from their original login, scraping data and executing operations as 'A1ice' on 'www.example.com'.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] If Alice was successfully duped and saved her credit card to the account, Mallory might then make purchases using that card.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Session identifiers in URL (query string, GET variables) or POST variables are not recommended as they simplify this attack – it is easy to make links or forms that set GET / POST variables.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Note: Cookies are shared between tabs and popped up browser windows.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] If your system requires to be hit with the same domain (www.example.com/?code=site1 and www.example.com/?code=site2 ), cookies may conflict with one another between tabs.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] It may be required to send the session identifier on the URL in order to overcome this limitation.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] If possible use site1.example.com or site2.example.com so there is no domain conflicts in the cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] This may incur costs with extra SSL certificates.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] This behavior can be seen on many sites by opening another tab and trying to do side by side search results.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] One of the sessions will become unusable.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Session identifiers in GET and POST were deprecated in PHP 8.4 and will be removed in PHP 9.0.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] This attack can be largely avoided by changing, regenerating the session ID when users log in.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] If every request specific to a user requires the user to be authenticated with ("logged into") the site, an attacker would need to know the id of the victim's log-in session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] When the victim visits the link with the fixed session id, however, they will need to log into their account in order to do anything "important" as themselves.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] At this point, their session id will change, and the attacker will not be able to do anything "important" with the anonymous session ID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] A similar technique can be used to solve the phishing problem.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] If the user protects their account with two passwords, then it can be solved to a great extent.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] This technique is also useful against cross-site request forgery attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] The session identifier on most modern systems is stored by default in an HTTP cookie, which has a moderate level of security as long as the session system disregards GET/POST values.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] However, this solution is vulnerable to cross-site request forgery, and it does not meet the statelessness requirement of REST.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] When enabling HTTPS security, some systems allow applications to obtain the SSL / TLS session identifier.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Use of the SSL/TLS session identifier is very secure, but many web development languages do not provide robust built-in functionality for this.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] A countermeasure against session fixation is to generate a new session identifier (SID) on each request.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] If this is done, then even though an attacker may trick a user into accepting a known SID, the SID will be invalid when the attacker attempts to re-use the SID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] `victim.example.com` accepts `SID=I_KNOW_THE_SID`, which would normally be bad.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] However, `victim.example.com` is secure because it performs session regeneration.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Alice will now use `SID=3134998145AB331F` that is unknown to Mallory, and `SID=I_KNOW_THE_SID` is invalid.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Mallory is thus unsuccessful in the session fixation attempt.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Unfortunately session regeneration is not always possible.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Problems are known to occur when third-party software such as ActiveX or Java applets are used, and when browser plugins communicate with the server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Third-party software could cause logouts, or the session could be split into two separate sessions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] If the implementation of sessions includes transmitting the SID through GET or POST variables, then this might also render the "back" button in most browsers unusable, as the user would then be using an older, invalid, session identifier from a previous request.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] One way to improve security is not to accept session identifiers that were not generated by the server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] However, as noted above, this does not prevent all session fixation attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] A logout function is useful as it allows users to indicate that a session should not allow further requests.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Thus attacks can only be effective while a session is active.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Note that the following code performs no Cross-site request forgery checks, potentially allowing an attacker to force users to log out of the web application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] This defense is simple to implement and has the advantage of providing a measure of protection against unauthorized users accessing an authorized user's account by using a machine that may have been left unattended.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Store a session variable containing a time stamp of the last access made by that SID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] When that SID is used again, compare the current timestamp with the one stored in the session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] If the difference is greater than a predefined number, say 5 minutes, destroy the session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Otherwise, update the session variable with the current timestamp.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] When visiting a page, most web browsers will set the Referrer header – the page that contained the link that you followed to get to this page.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] When the user is logged into a site that is not likely to be linked to from outside that site (e.g., banking websites, or webmail), and the site is not the kind of site where users would remain logged in for any great length of time, the Referrer should be from that site.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Any other Referrer should be considered suspicious.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] However, if the originating request is from a HTTPS page, then the referrer will be stripped, so you cannot depend on this security system.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] One way to further improve security is to ensure that the user appears to be the same end user (client).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] This makes it a bit harder to perform session fixation and other attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] As more and more networks begin to conform to RFC 3704 and other anti-spoofing practices, the IP address becomes more reliable as a "same source" identifier.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Therefore, the security of a web site can be improved by verifying that the source IP address is consistent throughout a session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] However, there are some points to consider before employing this approach.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] For some sites, the added security outweighs the lack of convenience, and for others it does not.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Browsers identify themselves by "User-Agent" HTTP headers.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] This header does not normally change during use; it would be extremely suspicious if that were to happen.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] A web application might make use of User-Agent detection in attempt to prevent malicious users from stealing sessions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] This however is trivial to bypass, as an attacker can easily capture the victim's user-agent with their own site and then spoof it during the attack.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] This proposed security system is relying on security through obscurity.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] But User Agent may change legally in few cases.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Defense in depth is to combine several countermeasures.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] The idea is simple: if one obstacle is trivial to overcome, several obstacles could be very hard to overcome.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] HTTP referrers are not passed with SSL/TLS (HTTPS).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] Note that this code checks the current REMOTE_ADDR (the user's IP address) and User-agent against the REMOTE_ADDR and User-agent of the previous request.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-fixation] This might be inconvenient for some sites as discussed above.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] In computer science, **session hijacking**, sometimes also known as **cookie hijacking**, is the exploitation of a valid computer session—sometimes also called a *session key*—to gain unauthorized access to information or services in a computer system.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] In particular, it is used to refer to the theft of a magic cookie used to authenticate a user to a remote server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] It has particular relevance to web developers, as the HTTP cookies used to maintain a session on many websites can be easily stolen by an attacker using an intermediary computer or with access to the saved cookies on the victim's computer (see HTTP cookie theft).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] After successfully stealing appropriate session cookies an adversary might use the Pass the Cookie technique to perform session hijacking.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Cookie hijacking is commonly used against client authentication on the internet.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Modern web browsers use cookie protection mechanisms to protect the web from being attacked.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] A popular method is using source-routed IP packets.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] This allows an attacker at point *B* on the network to participate in a conversation between *A* and *C* by encouraging the IP packets to pass through *B's* machine.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] If source-routing is turned off, the attacker can use "blind" hijacking, whereby it guesses the responses of the two machines.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Thus, the attacker can send a command, but can never see the response.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] However, a common command would be to set a password allowing access from elsewhere on the net.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] An attacker can also be "inline" between *A* and *C* using a sniffing program to watch the conversation.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] This is known as a "man-in-the-middle attack".
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] HTTP protocol versions 0.8 and 0.9 lacked cookies and other features necessary for session hijacking.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Version 0.9beta of Mosaic Netscape, released on October 13, 1994, supported cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Early versions of HTTP 1.0 did have some security weaknesses relating to session hijacking, but they were difficult to exploit due to the vagaries of most early HTTP 1.0 servers and browsers.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] As HTTP 1.0 has been designated as a fallback for HTTP 1.1 since the early 2000s—and as HTTP 1.0 servers are all essentially HTTP 1.1 servers the session hijacking problem has evolved into a nearly permanent security risk.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] The introduction of supercookies and other features with the modernized HTTP 1.1 has allowed for the hijacking problem to become an ongoing security problem.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Webserver and browser state machine standardization has contributed to this ongoing security problem.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] There are four main methods used to perpetrate a session hijack.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] After successfully acquiring appropriate session cookies an adversary would inject the session cookie into their browser to impersonate the victim user on the website from which the session cookie was stolen from.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Attackers often rely on specialized tools to execute session hijacking attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] One such tool is Firesheep, a Firefox extension introduced in October 2010.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Firesheep demonstrated session hijacking vulnerabilities in unsecured networks by capturing unencrypted cookies from popular websites, allowing users to take over active sessions of others on the same network.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] The tool worked by displaying potential targets in a sidebar, enabling session access without password theft.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Another widely used tool is Wireshark, a network protocol analyzer that allows attackers to monitor and intercept data packets on unsecured networks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] If a website does not encrypt its session cookies or authentication tokens, attackers can extract them and use them to gain unauthorized access to a victim’s account.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Firesheep, a Firefox extension introduced in October 2010, demonstrated session hijacking vulnerabilities in unsecured networks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] It captured unencrypted cookies from popular websites, allowing users to take over active sessions of others on the same network.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] The websites supported included Facebook, Twitter, Flickr, Amazon, Windows Live and Google, with the ability to use scripts to add other websites.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Only months later, Facebook and Twitter responded by offering (and later requiring) HTTP Secure throughout.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] DroidSheep is a simple Android tool for web session hijacking (sidejacking).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] It listens for HTTP packets sent via a wireless (802.11) network connection and extracts the session id from these packets in order to reuse them.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] DroidSheep can capture sessions using the libpcap library and supports: open (unencrypted) networks, WEP encrypted networks, and WPA/WPA2 encrypted networks (PSK only).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] This software uses libpcap and arpspoof.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] The apk was made available on Google Play but it has been taken down by Google.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] CookieCadger is a graphical Java app that automates sidejacking and replay of HTTP requests, to help identify information leakage from applications that use unencrypted GET requests.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] It is a cross-platform open-source utility based on the Wireshark suite which can monitor wired Ethernet, insecure Wi-Fi, or load a packet capture file for offline analysis.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Cookie Cadger has been used to highlight the weaknesses of youth team sharing sites such as Shutterfly (used by AYSO soccer league) and TeamSnap.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] CookieMonster is a man-in-the-middle exploit where a third party can gain HTTPS cookie data when the "Encrypted Sessions Only" property is not properly set.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] This could allow access to sites with sensitive personal or financial information.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] In 2008, this could affect major websites, including Gmail, Google Docs, eBay, Netflix, CapitalOne, Expedia.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] It is a Python based tool, developed by security researcher Mike Perry.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] Perry originally announced the vulnerability exploited by CookieMonster on BugTraq in 2007.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-hijacking] A year later, he demonstrated CookieMonster as a proof of concept tool at Defcon 16.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A web session is a sequence of network HTTP request and response transactions associated with the same user.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Modern and complex web applications require the retaining of information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, sessions provide the ability to establish variables – such as access rights and localization settings – which will apply to each and every interaction a user has with the web application for the duration of the session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Web applications can create sessions to keep track of anonymous users after the very first user request.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] An example would be maintaining the user language preference.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Additionally, web applications will make use of sessions once the user has authenticated.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This ensures the ability to identify the user on any subsequent requests as well as being able to apply security access controls, authorized access to the user private data, and to increase the usability of the application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, current web applications can provide session capabilities both pre and post authentication.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] See the OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] HTTP is a stateless protocol (RFC2616 section 5), where each request and response pair is independent of other web interactions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The session ID or token binds the user authentication credentials (in the form of a user session) to the user HTTP traffic and the appropriate access controls enforced by the web application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The disclosure, capture, prediction, brute force, or fixation of the session ID will lead to session hijacking (or sidejacking) attacks, where an attacker is able to fully impersonate a victim user in the web application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Attackers can perform two types of session hijacking attacks, targeted or generic.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In a targeted attack, the attacker's goal is to impersonate a specific (or privileged) web application victim user.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For generic attacks, the attacker's goal is to impersonate (or get access as) any valid or legitimate user in the web application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] With the goal of implementing secure session IDs, the generation of identifiers (IDs or tokens) must meet the following properties.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The name used by the session ID should not be extremely descriptive nor offer unnecessary details about the purpose and meaning of the ID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The session ID names used by the most common web application development frameworks can be easily fingerprinted, such as `PHPSESSID` (PHP), `JSESSIONID` (J2EE), `CFID` & `CFTOKEN` (ColdFusion), `ASP.NET_SessionId` (ASP .NET), etc.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, the session ID name can disclose the technologies and programming languages used by the web application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is recommended to change the default session ID name of the web development framework to a generic name, such as `id`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Session identifiers must have at least `64 bits` of entropy to prevent brute-force session guessing attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Entropy refers to the amount of randomness or unpredictability in a value.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Each “bit” of entropy doubles the number of possible outcomes, meaning a session ID with 64 bits of entropy can have `2^64` possible values.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A strong CSPRNG (Cryptographically Secure Pseudorandom Number Generator) must be used to generate session IDs.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This ensures the generated values are evenly distributed among all possible values.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Otherwise, attackers may be able to use statistical analysis techniques to identify patterns in how the session IDs are created, effectively reducing the entropy and allowing the attacker to guess or predict valid session IDs more easily.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] As mentioned in the previous *Session ID Entropy* section, a primary security requirement for session IDs is that they contain at least `64 bits` of entropy to prevent brute-force guessing attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Although session ID length matters, it's the entropy that ensures security.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The session ID must be long enough to encode sufficient entropy, preventing brute force attacks where an attacker guesses valid session IDs.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Different encoding methods can result in different lengths for the same amount of entropy.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Session IDs are often represented using hexadecimal encoding.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When using hexadecimal encoding, a session ID must be at least 16 hexadecimal characters long to achieve the required 64 bits of entropy.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Base64 or Microsoft's encoding for ASP.NET session IDs) a different number of characters may be required to represent the minimum 64 bits of entropy.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It’s important to note that if any part of the session ID is fixed or predictable, the effective entropy is reduced, and the length may need to be increased to compensate.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For example, if half of a 16-character hexadecimal session ID is fixed, only the remaining 8 characters are random, providing just 32 bits of entropy — which is insufficient for strong security.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] To maintain security, ensure that the entire session ID is randomly generated and unpredictable, or increase the overall length if parts of the ID are not random.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The session ID content (or value) must be meaningless to prevent information disclosure attacks, where an attacker is able to decode the contents of the ID and extract details of the user, the session, or the inner workings of the web application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The session ID must simply be an identifier on the client side, and its value must never include sensitive information or Personally Identifiable Information (PII).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] To read more about PII, refer to Wikipedia or this post.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The meaning and business or application logic associated with the session ID must be stored on the server side, and specifically, in session objects or in a session management database or repository.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The stored information can include the client IP address, User-Agent, email, username, user ID, role, privilege level, access rights, language preferences, account ID, current state, last login, session timeouts, and other internal session details.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If the session objects and properties contain sensitive information, such as credit card numbers, it is required to duly encrypt and protect the session management repository.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is recommended to use the session ID created by your language or framework.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If you need to create your own sessionID, use a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator (CSPRNG) with a size of at least 128 bits and ensure that each sessionID is unique.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The session management implementation defines the exchange mechanism that will be used between the user and the web application to share and continuously exchange the session ID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The preferred session ID exchange mechanism should allow defining advanced token properties, such as the token expiration date and time, or granular usage constraints.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This is one of the reasons why cookies (RFCs 2109 & 2965 & 6265) are one of the most extensively used session ID exchange mechanisms, offering advanced capabilities not available in other methods.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Web development frameworks, such as J2EE, ASP .NET, PHP, and others, provide their own session management features and associated implementation.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is recommended to use these built-in frameworks versus building a home made one from scratch, as they are used worldwide on multiple web environments and have been tested by the web application security and development communities over time.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The storage capabilities or repository used by the session management mechanism to temporarily save the session IDs must be secure, protecting the session IDs against local or remote accidental disclosure or unauthorized access.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A web application should make use of cookies for session ID exchange management.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If a user submits a session ID through a different exchange mechanism, such as a URL parameter, the web application should avoid accepting it as part of a defensive strategy to stop session fixation.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In order to protect the session ID exchange from active eavesdropping and passive disclosure in the network traffic, it is essential to use an encrypted HTTPS (TLS) connection for the entire web session, not only for the authentication process where the user credentials are exchanged.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This may be mitigated by HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) for a client that supports it.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Additionally, the `Secure` cookie attribute must be used to ensure the session ID is only exchanged through an encrypted channel.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The usage of an encrypted communication channel also protects the session against some session fixation attacks where the attacker is able to intercept and manipulate the web traffic to inject (or fix) the session ID on the victim's web browser.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] See the OWASP Transport Layer Security Cheat Sheet for more general guidance on implementing TLS securely.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is important to emphasize that TLS does not protect against session ID prediction, brute force, client-side tampering or fixation; however, it does provide effective protection against an attacker intercepting or stealing session IDs through a man in the middle attack.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The `Secure` cookie attribute instructs web browsers to only send the cookie through an encrypted HTTPS (SSL/TLS) connection.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This session protection mechanism is mandatory to prevent the disclosure of the session ID through MitM (Man-in-the-Middle) attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It ensures that an attacker cannot simply capture the session ID from web browser traffic.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The attacker can intercept and manipulate the victim user traffic and inject an HTTP unencrypted reference to the web application that will force the web browser to submit the session ID in the clear.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The `HttpOnly` cookie attribute instructs web browsers not to allow scripts (e.g.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] JavaScript or VBscript) an ability to access the cookies via the DOM document.cookie object.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This session ID protection is mandatory to prevent session ID stealing through XSS attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] However, if an XSS attack is combined with a CSRF attack, the requests sent to the web application will include the session cookie, as the browser always includes the cookies when sending requests.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The `HttpOnly` cookie only protects the confidentiality of the cookie; the attacker cannot use it offline, outside of the context of an XSS attack.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] See the OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The `SameSite` attribute prevents the browser from sending the cookie on cross-site requests, mitigating cross-origin leakage and providing CSRF defense.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Session cookies must explicitly set `SameSite=Strict` (preferred) or `SameSite=Lax`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Never use `SameSite=None` without `Secure`, and do not rely on the browser-default value, which varies across browsers and versions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The `Domain` cookie attribute instructs web browsers to only send the cookie to the specified domain and all subdomains.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If the attribute is not set, by default the cookie will only be sent to the origin server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The `Path` cookie attribute instructs web browsers to only send the cookie to the specified directory or subdirectories (or paths or resources) within the web application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If the attribute is not set, by default the cookie will only be sent for the directory (or path) of the resource requested and setting the cookie.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is recommended to use a narrow or restricted scope for these two attributes.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In this way, the `Domain` attribute should not be set (restricting the cookie just to the origin server) and the `Path` attribute should be set as restrictive as possible to the web application path that makes use of the session ID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Setting the `Domain` attribute to a too permissive value, such as `example.com` allows an attacker to launch attacks on the session IDs between different hosts and web applications belonging to the same domain, known as cross-subdomain cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For example, vulnerabilities in `www.example.com` might allow an attacker to get access to the session IDs from `secure.example.com`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Additionally, it is recommended not to mix web applications of different security levels on the same domain.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Vulnerabilities in one of the web applications would allow an attacker to set the session ID for a different web application on the same domain by using a permissive `Domain` attribute (such as `example.com`) which is a technique that can be used in session fixation attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Although the `Path` attribute allows the isolation of session IDs between different web applications using different paths on the same host, it is highly recommended not to run different web applications (especially from different security levels or scopes) on the same host.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Other methods can be used by these applications to access the session IDs, such as the `document.cookie` object.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Also, any web application can set cookies for any path on that host.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Cookies are vulnerable to DNS spoofing/hijacking/poisoning attacks, where an attacker can manipulate the DNS resolution to force the web browser to disclose the session ID for a given host or domain.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Session management mechanisms based on cookies can make use of two types of cookies, non-persistent (or session) cookies, and persistent cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If a cookie presents the `Max-Age` (that has preference over `Expires`) or `Expires` attributes, it will be considered a persistent cookie and will be stored on disk by the web browser based until the expiration time.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Typically, session management capabilities to track users after authentication make use of non-persistent cookies.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This forces the session to disappear from the client if the current web browser instance is closed.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, it is highly recommended to use non-persistent cookies for session management purposes, so that the session ID does not remain on the web client cache for long periods of time, from where an attacker can obtain it.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group (WHATWG) describes the HTML5 Web Storage APIs, `localStorage` and `sessionStorage`, as mechanisms for storing name-value pairs client-side.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Unlike HTTP cookies, the contents of `localStorage` and `sessionStorage` are not automatically shared within requests or responses by the browser and are used for storing data client-side.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Data stored using the `localStorage` API is accessible by pages which are loaded from the same origin, which is defined as the scheme (`https://`), host (`example.com`), port (`443`) and domain/realm (`example.com`).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This provides similar access to this data as would be achieved by using the `secure` flag on a cookie, meaning that data stored from `https` could not be retrieved via `http`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Due to potential concurrent access from separate windows/threads, data stored using `localStorage` may be susceptible to shared access issues (such as race-conditions) and should be considered non-locking (Web Storage API Spec).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Data stored using the `localStorage` API is persisted across browsing sessions, extending the timeframe in which it may be accessible to other system users.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The standards do not require `localStorage` data to be encrypted-at-rest, meaning it may be possible to directly access this data from disk.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] WHATWG suggests the use of `localStorage` for data that needs to be accessed across windows or tabs, across multiple sessions, and where large (multi-megabyte) volumes of data may need to be stored for performance reasons.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The `sessionStorage` API stores data within the window context from which it was called, meaning that Tab 1 cannot access data which was stored from Tab 2.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Also, like the `localStorage` API, data stored using the `sessionStorage` API is accessible by pages which are loaded from the same origin, which is defined as the scheme (`https://`), host (`example.com`), port (`443`) and domain/realm (`example.com`).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The `sessionStorage` API only stores data for the duration of the current browsing session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Once the tab is closed, that data is no longer retrievable.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This does not necessarily prevent access, should a browser tab be reused or left open.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Data may also persist in memory until a garbage collection event.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The standards do not require `sessionStorage` data to be encrypted-at-rest, meaning it may be possible to directly access this data from disk.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] WHATWG suggests the use of `sessionStorage` for data that is relevant for one-instance of a workflow, such as details for a ticket booking, but where multiple workflows could be performed in other tabs concurrently.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The window/tab bound nature will keep the data from leaking between workflows in separate tabs.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Web Workers run JavaScript code in a global context separate from the one of the current window.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A communication channel with the main execution window exists, which is called `MessageChannel`.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Web Workers are an alternative for browser storage of (session) secrets when storage persistence across page refresh is not a requirement.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For Web Workers to provide secure browser storage, any code that requires the secret should exist within the Web Worker and the secret should never be transmitted to the main window context.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Storing secrets within the memory of a Web Worker offers the same security guarantees as an HttpOnly cookie: the confidentiality of the secret is protected.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Still, an XSS attack can be used to send messages to the Web Worker to perform an operation that requires the secret.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The Web Worker will return the result of the operation to the main execution thread.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The advantage of a Web Worker implementation compared to an HttpOnly cookie is that a Web Worker allows for some isolated JavaScript code to access the secret; an HttpOnly cookie is not accessible to any JavaScript.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If the frontend JavaScript code requires access to the secret, the Web Worker implementation is the only browser storage option that preserves the secret confidentiality.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] There are two types of session management mechanisms for web applications, permissive and strict, related to session fixation vulnerabilities.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The session tokens should be handled by the web server if possible or generated via a cryptographically secure random number generator.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Although the most common mechanism in use today is the strict one (more secure), PHP defaults to permissive.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Developers must ensure that the web application does not use a permissive mechanism under certain circumstances.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Web applications should never accept a session ID they have never generated, and in case of receiving one, they should generate and offer the user a new valid session ID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Additionally, this scenario should be detected as a suspicious activity and an alert should be generated.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Session IDs must be considered untrusted, as any other user input processed by the web application, and they must be thoroughly validated and verified.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Depending on the session management mechanism used, the session ID will be received in a GET or POST parameter, in the URL or in an HTTP header (e.g. cookies).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The session ID must be renewed or regenerated by the web application after any privilege level change within the associated user session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The most common scenario where the session ID regeneration is mandatory is during the authentication process, as the privilege level of the user changes from the unauthenticated (or anonymous) state to the authenticated state though in some cases still not yet the authorized state.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Common scenarios to consider include; password changes, permission changes, or switching from a regular user role to an administrator role within the web application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For all sensitive pages of the web application, any previous session IDs must be ignored, only the current session ID must be assigned to every new request received for the protected resource, and the old or previous session ID must be destroyed.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The session ID regeneration is mandatory to prevent session fixation attacks, where an attacker sets the session ID on the victim user's web browser instead of gathering the victim's session ID, as in most of the other session-based attacks, and independently of using HTTP or HTTPS.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This protection mitigates the impact of other web-based vulnerabilities that can also be used to launch session fixation attacks, such as HTTP response splitting or XSS (see here and here).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A complementary recommendation is to use a different session ID or token name (or set of session IDs) pre and post authentication, so that the web application can keep track of anonymous users and authenticated users without the risk of exposing or binding the user session between both states.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If the web application uses cookies as the session ID exchange mechanism, and multiple cookies are set for a given session, the web application must verify all cookies (and enforce relationships between them) before allowing access to the user session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is very common for web applications to set a user cookie pre-authentication over HTTP to keep track of unauthenticated (or anonymous) users.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Once the user authenticates in the web application, a new post-authentication secure cookie is set over HTTPS, and a binding between both cookies and the user session is established.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If the web application does not verify both cookies for authenticated sessions, an attacker can make use of the pre-authentication unprotected cookie to get access to the authenticated user session (see here and here).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Web applications should try to avoid the same cookie name for different paths or domain scopes within the same web application, as this increases the complexity of the solution and potentially introduces scoping issues.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In order to minimize the time period an attacker can launch attacks over active sessions and hijack them, it is mandatory to set expiration timeouts for every session, establishing the amount of time a session will remain active.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Insufficient session expiration by the web application increases the exposure of other session-based attacks, as for the attacker to be able to reuse a valid session ID and hijack the associated session, it must still be active.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The shorter the session interval is, the lesser the time an attacker has to use the valid session ID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The session expiration timeout values must be set accordingly with the purpose and nature of the web application, and balance security and usability, so that the user can comfortably complete the operations within the web application without the session frequently expiring.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Both the idle and absolute timeout values are highly dependent on how critical the web application and its data are.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Common idle timeouts ranges are 2-5 minutes for high-value applications and 15-30 minutes for low risk applications.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Absolute timeouts depend on how long a user usually uses the application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If the application is intended to be used by an office worker for a full day, an appropriate absolute timeout range could be between 4 and 8 hours.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When a session expires, the web application must take active actions to invalidate the session on both sides, client and server.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The latter is the most relevant and mandatory from a security perspective.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For most session exchange mechanisms, client side actions to invalidate the session ID are based on clearing out the token value.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] All sessions should implement an idle or inactivity timeout.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This timeout defines the amount of time a session will remain active in case there is no activity in the session, closing and invalidating the session upon the defined idle period since the last HTTP request received by the web application for a given session ID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The idle timeout limits the chances an attacker has to guess and use a valid session ID from another user.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] However, if the attacker is able to hijack a given session, the idle timeout does not limit the attacker's actions, as they can generate activity on the session periodically to keep the session active for longer periods of time.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Session timeout management and expiration must be enforced server-side.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If the client is used to enforce the session timeout, for example using the session token or other client parameters to track time references (e.g. number of minutes since login time), an attacker could manipulate these to extend the session duration.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] All sessions should implement an absolute timeout, regardless of session activity.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This timeout defines the maximum amount of time a session can be active, closing and invalidating the session upon the defined absolute period since the given session was initially created by the web application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] After invalidating the session, the user is forced to (re)authenticate again in the web application and establish a new session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The absolute session limits the amount of time an attacker can use a hijacked session and impersonate the victim user.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Alternatively, the web application can implement an additional renewal timeout after which the session ID is automatically renewed, in the middle of the user session, and independently of the session activity and, therefore, of the idle timeout.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] After a specific amount of time since the session was initially created, the web application can regenerate a new ID for the user session and try to set it, or renew it, on the client.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The previous session ID value would still be valid for some time, accommodating a safety interval, before the client is aware of the new ID and starts using it.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] At that time, when the client switches to the new ID inside the current session, the application invalidates the previous ID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This scenario minimizes the amount of time a given session ID value, potentially obtained by an attacker, can be reused to hijack the user session, even when the victim user session is still active.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The user session remains alive and open on the legitimate client, although its associated session ID value is transparently renewed periodically during the session duration, every time the renewal timeout expires.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, the renewal timeout complements the idle and absolute timeouts, specially when the absolute timeout value extends significantly over time (e.g. it is an application requirement to keep the user sessions open for long periods of time).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Depending on the implementation, potentially there could be a race condition where the attacker with a still valid previous session ID sends a request before the victim user, right after the renewal timeout has just expired, and obtains first the value for the renewed session ID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] At least in this scenario, the victim user might be aware of the attack as the session will be suddenly terminated because the associated session ID is not valid anymore.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Web applications should provide mechanisms that allow security aware users to actively close their session once they have finished using the web application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Web applications must provide a visible and easily accessible logout (logoff, exit, or close session) button that is available on the web application header or menu and reachable from every web application resource and page, so that the user can manually close the session at any time.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] As described in *Session_Expiration* section, the web application must invalidate the session at least on server side.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Even after the session has ended, private or sensitive data exchanged during the session may still be accessible through the web browser's cache.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] To mitigate this, web applications must use restrictive cache directives for all HTTP and HTTPS traffic.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This includes the use of HTTP headers such as `Cache-Control` and `Pragma`, or equivalent `<meta>` tags on all pages—especially those displaying sensitive content.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Session identifiers must never be cached.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] To prevent this, it is highly recommended to include the `Cache-Control: no-store` directive in responses containing session IDs.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Unlike `no-cache`, which allows caching but requires revalidation, `no-store` ensures that the response (including headers like `Set-Cookie`) is never stored in any cache.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In addition to preventing future caching, applications should ensure that previously stored sensitive data is removed when a session ends.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This can be achieved by returning the Clear-Site-Data response header (for example, `Clear-Site-Data: "cache", "cookies", "storage"`) during logout or session termination.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This instructs the browser to delete cached resources, cookies, and other client-side storage associated with the origin, helping ensure a complete session cleanup.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] To ensure session integrity and account protection, applications should require reauthentication when specific high-risk events are detected.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Requiring reauthentication helps mitigate session hijacking and unauthorized access—especially when long-lived sessions or external identity providers are in use.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Web applications can complement the previously described session management defenses with additional countermeasures on the client side.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Client-side protections, typically in the form of JavaScript checks and verifications, are not bullet proof and can easily be defeated by a skilled attacker, but can introduce another layer of defense that has to be bypassed by intruders.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Web applications can use JavaScript code in the login page to evaluate and measure the amount of time since the page was loaded and a session ID was granted.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If a login attempt is tried after a specific amount of time, the client code can notify the user that the maximum amount of time to log in has passed and reload the login page, hence retrieving a new session ID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This extra protection mechanism tries to force the renewal of the session ID pre-authentication, avoiding scenarios where a previously used (or manually set) session ID is reused by the next victim using the same computer, for example, in session fixation attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Web applications can use JavaScript code to capture all the web browser tab or window close (or even back) events and take the appropriate actions to close the current session before closing the web browser, emulating that the user has manually closed the session via the logout button.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Web applications can use JavaScript code once the user has logged in and a session has been established to force the user to re-authenticate if a new web browser tab or window is opened against the same web application.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The web application does not want to allow multiple web browser tabs or windows to share the same session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, the application tries to force the web browser to not share the same session ID simultaneously between them.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] JavaScript code can be used by the web application in all (or critical) pages to automatically logout client sessions after the idle timeout expires, for example, by redirecting the user to the logout page (the same resource used by the logout button mentioned previously).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The benefit of enhancing the server-side idle timeout functionality with client-side code is that the user can see that the session has finished due to inactivity, or even can be notified in advance that the session is about to expire through a count down timer and warning messages.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This user-friendly approach helps to avoid loss of work in web pages that require extensive input data due to server-side silently expired sessions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] If an attacker tries to guess or brute force a valid session ID, they need to launch multiple sequential requests against the target web application using different session IDs from a single (or set of) IP address(es).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Additionally, if an attacker tries to analyze the predictability of the session ID (e.g. using statistical analysis), they need to launch multiple sequential requests from a single (or set of) IP address(es) against the target web application to gather new valid session IDs.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Web applications must be able to detect both scenarios based on the number of attempts to gather (or use) different session IDs and alert and/or block the offending IP address(es).
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Web applications should focus on detecting anomalies associated to the session ID, such as its manipulation.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] The OWASP AppSensor Project provides a framework and methodology to implement built-in intrusion detection capabilities within web applications focused on the detection of anomalies and unexpected behaviors, in the form of detection points and response actions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] With the goal of detecting (and, in some scenarios, protecting against) user misbehaviors and session hijacking, it is highly recommended to bind the session ID to other user or client properties, such as the client IP address, User-Agent, or client-based digital certificate.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] If the web application detects any change or anomaly between these different properties in the middle of an established session, this is a very good indicator of session manipulation and hijacking attempts, and this simple fact can be used to alert and/or terminate the suspicious session.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Although these properties cannot be used by web applications to trustingly defend against session attacks, they significantly increase the web application detection (and protection) capabilities.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Web applications should increase their logging capabilities by including information regarding the full life cycle of sessions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Sensitive data like the session ID should not be included in the logs in order to protect the session logs against session ID local or remote disclosure or unauthorized access.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] However, some kind of session-specific information must be logged in order to correlate log entries to specific sessions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] It is recommended to log a salted-hash of the session ID instead of the session ID itself in order to allow for session-specific log correlation without exposing the session ID.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] In particular, web applications must thoroughly protect administrative interfaces that allow to manage all the current active sessions.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Frequently these are used by support personnel to solve session related issues, or even general issues, by impersonating the user and looking at the web application as the user does.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] The session logs become one of the main web application intrusion detection data sources, and can also be used by intrusion protection systems to automatically terminate sessions and/or disable user accounts when (one or many) attacks are detected.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] If active protections are implemented, these defensive actions must be logged too.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] It is the web application design decision to determine if multiple simultaneous logons from the same user are allowed from the same or from different client IP addresses.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] In these scenarios, or to complement the web application defenses, and with the goal of keeping the web application as secure as possible, it is recommended to use external protections such as Web Application Firewalls (WAFs) that can mitigate the session management threats already described.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Web Application Firewalls offer detection and protection capabilities against session based attacks.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] On the one hand, it is trivial for WAFs to enforce the usage of security attributes on cookies, such as the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` flags, applying basic rewriting rules on the `Set-Cookie` header for all the web application responses that set a new cookie.
[src:session-fixation-defense/session-management-cheat-sheet-p02] The open-source ModSecurity WAF, plus the OWASP Core Rule Set, provide capabilities to detect and apply security cookie attributes, countermeasures against session fixation attacks, and session tracking features to enforce sticky sessions.
